<h1>Experimental palette</h1>

<p>Not married to the specific colors here. I'm more interested in exploring systems approaches to color.</p>

<p>This experiment limits the number of colors in the palette to only 7. Light and dark versions of each color are provided.</p>

<p>The goal here is to limit the number of colors a designer needs to think about, while still providing flexibility.</p>

<p>In common usage, these colors are divided into:<p> 

<ul>
	<li>3 surface colors (or backgrounds)</li> 
	<li>3 line colors (for text and icons)</li>
	<li>1 call-to-action color</p>
</ul>

<p>Finally, while I didn't do any fine tuning on the colors, I did generate all of the palettes on the same lightness curve using OKLCH. It's possible to use math to simplify this palette (by dynamically adding alpha or lightness in code). But I figured I'd just do the whole thing to get nicer hue/chroma for each tint/shade.</p>

{% set colors = [ "coastal", "desert", "mountain", "valley", "gray-cool", "gray-warm", "danger", "ongoing", "warning",
"success", "info" ] %}

{% for color in colors %}
	<h2>{{ color }}</h2>
	<svg width="1050" height="370">
		<style>
			text { font-size: .75rem; }
		</style>
		<rect width="450" height="50" y="0" x="0" fill="lightgrey" />
		<text text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="middle" x="225" y="25" fill="dimgray">Light tints</text>
		<rect width="150" height="50" y="0" x="450" fill="dimgray" />
		<text text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="middle" x="525" y="25" fill="white">CTA</text>
		<rect width="450" height="50" y="0" x="600" fill="black" />
		<text text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="middle" x="825" y="25" fill="silver">Dark shades</text>
		{% for n in range(1,8) %}
			{% set textZ = 1 if n > 3 else 7 %}
			<rect width="150" height="30" y="60" x="{{150*(n-1)}}" fill="var(--{{color}}-{{n}}-dark)" />
			<text text-anchor="start" dominant-baseline="middle" x="{{150*(n-1) + 10}}" y="75" fill="var(--{{color}}-{{textZ}})">{{color}}-{{n}}-dark</text>
